Executive Summary

This study highlights the value of the US Imports - Automated Manifest System Shipments 2018-2020 or AMS dataset in understanding the effects of policies on global supply chains and international trade. Leveraging big data techniques, this study analyzed the dataset to gain insights into the movement of shipments and ocean freights and the governing policies behind them. The results underscored the importance of trade agreements, shipment delays, the COVID-19 pandemic, and geopolitical risks in shaping the shipping industry. The study emphasizes the need for evaluating trade policies, improving shipment processes, and adapting to disruptions. To further enhance similar works, future recommendations include expanding the timeline coverage and exploring the impact of tariff policies and other freight modes.

The key to accessing this data was its free subscription in AWS Data Exchange and its readiness for transfer between S3 buckets. After transferring the data, we were able to easily perform initial exploratory data analysis (EDA) using EMR. We had set up instances with 1 core and 3 worker nodes, allowing us to efficiently shortlist the files. Once we had identified the key datasets (header, shipper, and container), we converted them to the Parquet format. This conversion resulted in a significant file size reduction of around 82%, leading to savings in storage and faster processing. We then ran the EDA on the EMR cluster to generate our descriptive analytics. Each of the PySpark dataframes was converted to pandas format and exported as csv files written to our S3 bucket. To create the report and visualizations, we transferred the extracted csv files to Jojie using AWS CLI.

The technical analysis focused on preprocessing the AMS dataset using big data techniques to explore the influence of policies on global and transnational shipments. Descriptive analytics provided insights into the dynamics of international trade, emphasizing the significance of trade agreements, shipment delays, the COVID-19 pandemic, and geopolitical risks. The study highlights the importance of evaluating trade policies, improving shipment processes, and adapting to disruptions. Future research suggestions involve expanding the timeline coverage and investigating the impact of tariff policies and other freight modes to gain a comprehensive understanding of trade dynamics.

Combining cloud (AWS) and big data techniques has allowed us to maximize the insights we can glean from the data. Through the techniques we applied, we discovered numerous opportunities to enhance its utilization while reducing costs. To advance knowledge in this field, it is recommended that future studies expand the timeline coverage beyond 2018-2020. This expansion will enable a broader understanding of trade dynamics and their evolution over time. Moreover, investigating the impact of tariff policies and exploring other freight modes beyond ocean shipments would provide valuable insights into the broader transportation landscape and its influence on global trade. Conducting these studies would contribute to a deeper understanding of policy effects and assist in informed decision-making within the realm of international trade and supply chain management.

Problem Statement

The policies governing global supply chain, international trade, and tariffs can have a significant influence on the movement of shipments worldwide. However, comprehending the effects of these factors and their implications for businesses and economies necessitates a thorough analysis and exploration.

To shed light on these dynamics, we will leverage the US Imports Automated Manifest System Shipments 2018-2020 or AMS dataset. Through descriptive analytics, our objective is to address the following key questions:

  1. Which countries exhibit the highest shipment volumes? How does the presence of an active free trade agreement with the United States impact this?
  2. Which shippers and countries experience the most delays? What may be the implications of these delayed shipments?
  3. How do the number and scheduling of shipments evolve over time?
  4. How do unforeseen events, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, influence shipment trends?

Motivation

Recent events, such as the financial crisis of 2008-2009 and the global lockdown due to the COVID-19 pandemic, have demonstrated the potential impact on the global supply chain and international trade. While the concept of deglobalization has been debunked (Shulga, 2023), it is evident that external factors can significantly affect these domains.

Efficiencies and cost savings are key benefits of a global supply chain, enabling businesses to reach customers worldwide quickly and cost-effectively (Williams, 2023). However, factors like tariffs (York, 2018), protectionism (Shulga, 2023) (York, 2018), and free trade agreements can create binding constraints on ocean freight movements. Moreover, geopolitical turmoil and environmental disasters (Williams, 2023) pose additional challenges for the global supply chain.

To address these complexities, our analysis of the AMS dataset aims to provide valuable insights into the effects of these factors on the import landscape. By exploring trade patterns, identifying disruptions in supply chains, and understanding business resilience, we can empower stakeholders to make informed decisions and strategic plans. This analysis will enable policymakers, businesses, and researchers to gain a deeper understanding of the dynamics within the ocean freight industry, adapt policies and agreements when necessary, and enhance decision-making processes.

By examining the interplay among global supply chain dynamics, international trade policies, and the impact of external events, this study shall contribute to a broader understanding of how businesses can navigate challenges, promote growth, and foster resilience in the face of a rapidly changing transnational trade landscape.

Data Source and Exploration

The AMS dataset (Enigma, n.d.) is a comprehensive collection of millions of data points pertaining to shipments to various ports in the United States. This dataset is meticulously compiled by the US Customs and Border Protection and encompasses vital information such as manufacturer details, shipper contact information, vessel country codes, carrier information, and cargo descriptions. Its extensive scope makes it an invaluable resource for analyzing global supply chains, investigating international trade dynamics, examining the effects of tariffs, and probing trafficking felonies. For this study, the primary focus revolves around the analysis of global supply chains and international trade, as these aspects significantly shape the research objectives.

The study places particular emphasis on exploring the fully normalized relational database structure of the AMS dataset, which encompasses three key tables: the header, shipper, and container tables (refer to Image 1). The header table serves as the central repository of vessel details, shipment summaries, as well as target and actual arrival information. Complementing this, the shipper table provides insights into the companies responsible for shipping the vessels. Lastly, the container table delineates the various container types employed in each shipment.

Image 1. AMS Dataset Tables.
Different tables under the AMS dataset and the corresponding objects they contain.

The dataset has a total size of 63.7GB distributed across 33 separate files covering the years 2018, 2019, and 2020. For this study, we will be utilizing 25.4GB (refer to Image 2) of data from the three tables mentioned above.

Image 2. AMS Dataset Size.
Total size of the dataset to be utilized for this project.

Data Description

The AMS dataset, available on AWS Data Exchange, offers valuable insights into the intricacies of global supply chains, international trade, and tariff effects. To access the dataset, a free subscription to AWS Data Exchange is required, and subsequent data processing involves transferring the files in CSV format to an S3 bucket. The dataset, along with its comprehensive description, can be accessed here.

Table 1 provides an overview of the row count for each table within the AMS dataset. Notably, a specific filter was applied to the Header Row Count, which involved considering data entries with non-null values for actual_arrival_date and vessel_country_code. This filter ensures that the analysis focuses on shipments with available and relevant information. Furthermore, the dataset covers target and actual arrival dates spanning the years 2018 to 2020, allowing for a comprehensive examination of shipment trends during this period.

Data Limitation

The dataset for this study consists of multiple files stored in the S3 bucket of the data source. To optimize the analysis, we have carefully selected the latest extracts based on their extraction dates, ensuring access to the most up-to-date and comprehensive data.

To maintain the integrity of the analysis and focus on relevant insights, we have excluded data points outside the timeframe of 2018 to 2020. These excluded records typically contain a limited number of data points, often used for testing purposes, and may only consist of a few hundred or thousand rows. Including such records in our analysis could introduce potential biases and impact accurate month-on-month or year-on-year comparisons.

The study primarily focuses on three specific tables within the dataset to explore temporal aspects, including the volume of shipments, country performance, shipper performance, and commonly used services. These tables provide valuable insights into the dynamics of the dataset. However, analyzing port and shipper geographic details was not feasible due to the extensive mapping required for addresses, the need for standardizing city, state, and country names, and the significant cleansing efforts involved. Given the dataset's size, consisting of millions of data points, these tasks would have been resource-intensive and thus, will not be covered by this study.

It's important to note that fields not specifically mentioned in this study were not utilized in the analysis. However, these unused fields could be explored in future studies or analyses, providing additional insights and expanding the scope of understanding within the dataset.

Methodology

Image 6. Methodology.
Overview of the steps followed for this study.


Data Collection

We subscribed to the AMS dataset within the AWS Data Exchange Subscription to gain access to the dataset.

S3 File Transfer

We established a dedicated S3 bucket and performed the necessary data transfer from the original AMS S3 bucket. This transfer was executed using the AWS user interface.

Data Exploration

To conduct a thorough exploratory data analysis (EDA), we leveraged the power of EMR and the flexibility of PySpark. This approach was particularly advantageous given the large size of the dataset and the presence of multiple files.

By harnessing the capabilities of EMR and PySpark, we were able to efficiently process and analyze the interrelationships between the various files. During the initial investigation, we confirmed that the header table contains the primary transactional details, and subsequently decided to include the shipper and container files for a comprehensive analysis.

One notable advantage of using EMR and PySpark was the ability to handle the entire dataset without any limitations. Even with the fully loaded files for each table, the query performance remained remarkably fast, allowing us to retrieve and explore insights more quickly.

Conversion to Parquet

To further enhance query speed and reduce file size, we converted all 9 files (3 files for each table) into 3 separate Parquet objects. This conversion resulted in a file size reduction from the original 25.4GB down to only 4.5GB.

Data Filtering

Based on the initial EDA, we identified specific filters for rows where the arrival and estimated dates fall outside the 2018-2020 range. We also filtered out rows where the vessel_country_code and actual_arrival_date are null. We also did not perform any data cleaning as the needed fields are already sufficient.

Feature Engineering

Additionally, we performed feature engineering on columns derived from the estimated_arrival_date and actual_arrival_date, including extracting the year, month, and year-month format. We also calculated an is_delayed field based on the estimated and actual arrival dates. These engineered features facilitated easier query building and report generation. The code for these transformations was implemented during the loading of the Parquet files for the header table.

Data Extraction

Due to the efficient processing on EMR, we did not limit the data, as it could be processed within a few seconds. We converted the PySpark dataframes to pandas dataframes and wrote the extracted data into CSV files, which were saved in the S3 bucket under the directory extracted_csv/. These tasks were performed in a separate notebook titled bdcc-lab-2.ipynb.

Exploratory Data Analysis and Report Generation

Descriptive analytics reports were generated using Matplotlib module, taking advantage of the fact that the data now fits in memory. The findings and conclusions for each report are documented in the remaining sections of the notebook.

Results and Discussion

We conducted an exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the extracted tables from the AWS dataset to address our problem statements. The EDA consisted of four main components: Shipments, Delays, Trends, and Disruptions.

In the Shipments analysis, we examined the number of shipments per country as recorded in the dataset. This allowed us to explore the trade relationships between these countries and the United States.

Under the Delays section, we investigated the extent of delays in shipments. Specifically, we analyzed the number of days by which shipments from different countries and shippers were delayed.

For the Trends component, we examined the monthly pattern of shipment volumes from 2018 to 2020. This analysis provided us with an overview of the fluctuation in shipment numbers over time.

Lastly, we explored Disruptions to identify any current events that may have impacted shipments during the covered period. This analysis helped us understand external factors that could potentially influence the shipment data.

Shipments

To focus specifically on the trade relationship between countries and the United States, we temporarily removed information related to the United States from the dataset. Additionally, we excluded locations falling under the following categories: (1) locations that no longer exist, (2) US territories, and (3) territories claimed by another official country. Figure 1. Countries with the Highest Number of Shipments.
These are the ten countries with the highest recorded shipments from 2018 to 2020.

The top countries in terms of the number of shipments, as shown in Figure 1, include Panama, Liberia, and Hong Kong. These countries exhibit different trade relationships with the United States, which contributes to their shipment volumes.

Panama stands out as a significant trading partner with the United States, benefiting from an existing and comprehensive free trade agreement, among other trade agreements (International Trade Administration, n.d.). With its strategic location and the Panama Canal facilitating faster transportation, it is not surprising that Panama ranks highest in terms of shipments. The accessibility and proximity to the United States play a crucial role in fostering strong trade ties.

Although Liberia and Hong Kong do not have a formal free trade agreement with the United States, they have established trade and investment agreements that provide them with certain trade benefits. Liberia, for instance, enjoys duty-free and preferential trade benefits, as well as access to the US market through its three trade and investment agreements with the United States (International Trade Administration, n.d.).

In the case of Hong Kong, its unique position between the United States and China positions it as an important trade hub for US firms seeking to expand into the Chinese market (International Trade Administration, n.d.). Hong Kong maximizes trade opportunities, benefiting from both its trade relationship with the United States and its closer ties with mainland China, with which it has a free trade agreement (International Trade Administration, n.d.).

Figure 2. Countries with the Lowest Number of Shipments.
These are the ten countries with the lowest recorded shipments from 2018 to 2020.

Among the listed countries, Tonga, New Caledonia, and Peru have the lowest shipment volumes, with less than 70 recorded shipments over the three-year period from 2018 to 2020. This makes them the "cellar dwellers" in terms of trade activity.

Peru's inclusion in this group is surprising because it has an active Free Trade Agreement (FTA) with the US and is geographically close to the US. The presence of an FTA typically facilitates trade by reducing trade barriers and promoting economic cooperation. However, despite these advantages, Peru's shipment volume remains low.

One potential factor that could contribute to Peru's low shipment volume is the absence of a bilateral taxation treaty (International Trade Agreement, n.d.) between Peru and the US. This absence may lead to challenges related to double taxation for Peruvian businesses operating in the US. Double taxation (Hayes, 2022) occurs when a business is taxed on its income in both its home country (Peru) and the foreign country (US). This can create additional costs and administrative burdens for Peruvian businesses, which may impact their trade activities and discourage higher shipment volumes.

# Load the dictionary from the file
with open('country_dict.pkl', 'rb') as file:
    country_dict = pickle.load(file)

with open('country_dict_df.pkl', 'rb') as file:
    country_dict_df = pickle.load(file)

# load the world shapefile data
world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))

# define the countries to highlight and their respective weights
country_count = (df_all_countries[['vessel_country_code', '% Total']]
                 .sort_values('% Total',
                              ascending=False).values.tolist())

# create a new column 'highlight' with default value 0
world['highlight'] = 0

# set the 'highlight' value to the specified weight for the selected countries
for country, count in country_count:
    world.loc[world['name'] == country_dict.get(country), 'highlight'] = count

# Define the custom colormap
cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('teal_cmap', ['#ffffff',
                                                               '#4472C4'])
    
# plot the world map with highlighted countries
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 8))
divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.1)
world.plot(ax=ax,
           column='highlight',
           cmap=cmap,
           linewidth=0.5, 
           edgecolor='black', 
           legend=True,
           cax=cax)

# set ocean color and style
ax.set_facecolor('#f1ffff')

# remove spines
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)

# set the limits for the latitude axis to exclude the poles
ax.set_ylim(-60, 90)

# show plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Figure 4. US FTA Partners with the Highest Number of Shipments.
These are the ten US FTA partners with the highest recorded shipments from 2018 to 2020.

As shown in Figure 4, and observed earlier in Figure 1, Panama and Singapore stand out as the two countries with the highest shipment counts among US FTA partners. Notably, their shipment numbers surpass the mean by a significant margin. In contrast, the remaining countries exhibit considerably lower shipment counts, with five countries (El Salvador, Guatemala, Jordan, Korea, and Nicaragua) recording no shipments at all from 2018 to 2020.

It is important to consider that various practical disadvantages associated with FTAs (3. FTAs - advantages and disadvantages, n.d.) may have influenced these shipment numbers for the other eighteen FTA partners. Factors such as the increasing complexity of the international trading system, which can raise transaction costs for businesses, resource-intensive negotiations, and the complex enforcement of different rules negotiated under these agreements, may have impacted the trade volume. These practical disadvantages highlight the challenges and complexities involved in navigating the international trade landscape and implementing effective trade agreements.

Figure 5. Non-US FTA Partners with the Highest Number of Shipments.

Figure 5 reveals that eight of the countries listed entered the top ten countries with the highest number of shipments, as observed in Figure 1. Interestingly, these countries have managed to achieve significant shipment volumes without having an FTA with US. This suggests that they may be able to operate relatively free from the potential disadvantages mentioned earlier associated with FTAs.

One notable country in Figure 5 is the United Kingdom, which commenced its trade agreement negotiation with the United States in 2019 (Broadbent, 2023). Given the UK's status as the largest European investor in the US and its position as the third-largest goods export market for the US (among non-FTA partners observed in Figure 5) or fifth-largest overall (among all countries observed in Figure 1), the initiation of trade agreement negotiations is not surprising. This trade agreement holds tremendous economic and strategic benefits for both economies (Broadbent, 2023) and reflects their aspirations for closer trade ties. It is possible that other countries on this list may also pursue trade agreement negotiations, if not already underway, based on their shipment volumes to the US and the potential benefits they can derive from such agreements.

Figure 10. Non-US FTA Partners with the Highest Shipment Delays.
These are the top ten non-US FTA partners associated with the greatest number of days of shipment delays.

The ten non-US partners with the highest shipment delays recorded an average delay of at least five days for their shipments, as seen in Figure 10. While these countries are not bound by the rules and regulations of a trade agreement, it is important for them to examine their shipment time management practices as efficient and timely shipments are crucial for businesses to maintain a competitive edge in the global market. The significant delays observed in these countries pose risks to individual businesses and can potentially impact customer satisfaction.

Overall, it is important to note that delayed shipments may not always be attributed solely to the actions of the shippers themselves. There are various external factors that can contribute to delays, which are often beyond the control (Freightos, n.d.) of the shippers.

Global events and disruptions, such as natural disasters, political unrest, or pandemics, can have a significant impact on the movement of goods and lead to shipment delays. These unforeseen circumstances can disrupt supply chains, cause port congestion, and result in logistical challenges.

Port congestion and traffic are common issues that affect the shipping industry. Limited infrastructure, inadequate port capacity, or inefficient operations can lead to delays in the handling and processing of shipments. These challenges can arise from the complex relationship between shipping lines and port authorities, which need to be effectively managed to ensure smooth operations.

Unpredictable weather conditions, particularly for freights navigating through tumultuous and unstable bodies of water, can also contribute to shipment delays. Adverse weather events such as storms, hurricanes, or heavy fog can disrupt maritime transportation and force vessels to alter their routes or wait for safer conditions before proceeding.

While shippers play a crucial role in ensuring timely shipments, it is essential to consider these external factors that can impact the delivery timeline. Collaborative efforts among shippers, carriers, port authorities, and other stakeholders are necessary to mitigate the effects of these challenges and find solutions to minimize delays.

Trends

The outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020 had far-reaching implications for various industries worldwide, including international trade and shipping. The implementation of lockdowns, travel restrictions, and social distancing measures significantly disrupted global supply chains and logistics networks.

In examining the trends in shipment counts from 2018 to 2020, we have a unique opportunity to explore the impact of the global pandemic that occurred in 2020, leveraging historical data from the preceding years. Specifically, we are interested in investigating the effect of COVID-19 on ocean freights and shipment deliveries.

Figure 11. Trend in Total Monthly Shipments.
Illustration of the trend in total monthly shipments from January 2018 to September 2020.

As we examine Figure 11, we can clearly observe the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the shipment counts. The onset of the pandemic, highlighted by the prominent decline in February and March of 2020, brought about a significant disruption to global operations, affecting almost all industries except essential services such as healthcare. The shipping industry was no exception and experienced a considerable slowdown during the initial lockdown period.

The strict restrictions and containment measures implemented to curb the spread of the virus resulted in temporary shutdowns of manufacturing facilities, reduced consumer demand, and logistical challenges. These factors contributed to the decline in shipment counts during the early months of the pandemic.

However, as the months progressed and governments began to gradually ease restrictions, we can observe a notable spike in shipment counts from June to August. This increase can be attributed to the resumption of economic activities and the gradual reopening of businesses in many parts of the world. As industries adapted to the new normal and implemented safety protocols, the shipping industry also saw a recovery in terms of shipment volumes.

It is important to note that the sudden drop in shipment counts in September is due to the limitation of available data, as the dataset only extends up to that period. Therefore, the decline does not necessarily reflect an actual decrease in shipments but rather a data limitation.

Additionally, the spike in shipment counts from June to August may also be influenced by the upgrading of logistics services during the pandemic crisis. As logistics services, including the shipping industry, were deemed essential for the movement of goods without risking infection among people, efforts were made to enhance these services. This could have led to an increased demand for logistics and shipping, resulting in the observed spike in shipment counts during that period.

We can observe in Figure 12 some interesting trends in shipment counts at the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic. Contrary to expectations, both Panama and Singapore experienced a slight increase in shipments during this period, while Israel maintained a relatively consistent monthly shipment trend.

The increase in shipments for Panama and Singapore during the early months of the pandemic could be attributed to several factors. One possible explanation is that these countries, being major shipping hubs and international trade centers, continued to play a crucial role in facilitating global trade even amid the pandemic. As other regions and countries faced disruptions and restrictions, businesses may have relied more on these well-established shipping routes and logistics networks to ensure the flow of essential goods.

Another factor to consider is the specific industries and goods that these countries specialize in. Panama, for instance, is known for its strategic location and the Panama Canal, which serves as a vital trade artery connecting the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. The canal's efficiency and importance for international shipping could have contributed to the sustained shipment activity in Panama during the early months of the pandemic.

Similarly, Singapore, as a global financial and logistics hub, has a well-developed infrastructure and strong connectivity with international markets. This could have allowed the country to maintain a relatively stable level of shipments, especially for essential goods and commodities.

Figure 14. Trend in Total Monthly Shipments of Russia and Ukraine.
These are the monthly shipment trend of non-US FTA partners with the highest number of shipments.

The Russo-Ukrainian war, which escalated in February 2022 with the invasion of Ukraine by Russia (Financial Times, n.d.), has had significant implications for the trade dynamics between the two countries and their relationships with the United States. It is important to note that the origins of this conflict can be traced back to 2014 (Congressional Research Service, 2023), when tensions between Russia and Ukraine began to rise.

The ongoing war and geopolitical tensions have undoubtedly impacted the shipment volumes between Russia and the US (see Figure 14). As shown in the data, there is a noticeable decline in the shipment counts for Russia, which can be attributed to several factors. Firstly, the economic sanctions imposed on Russia by the US and its allies in response to the conflict (Congressional Research Service, 2022) have had a direct impact on trade activities between the two nations. These sanctions, aimed at pressuring Russia to change its behavior, have limited trade opportunities and created barriers to commerce.

Additionally, the strained relationship between Russia and the US may have influenced the trade dynamics. The political and diplomatic tensions resulting from the conflict have likely affected business confidence and led to a decrease in trade activities. Furthermore, the impact of the conflict on Russia's economy and infrastructure may have hindered its ability to engage in international trade.

On the other hand, the relationship between Ukraine and the US, particularly in the context of the conflict with Russia, may have contributed to a greater number of shipments to the US. The US has been supportive of Ukraine throughout the crisis (U.S. Embassy Kiev, 2023), providing economic and military assistance. This support, combined with the strategic importance of Ukraine in the region, may have resulted in increased trade flows between Ukraine and the US.

Conclusion

Case Study

This Shipments section highlights the complex dynamics of international trade and emphasizes the significance of trade agreements, taxation policies, and strategic partnerships in shaping shipment volumes between countries.

The presence of Free Trade Agreements has influenced shipment volumes, with Panama and Singapore leading among the US FTA partners. However, practical disadvantages associated with FTAs may have affected trade volumes for other partner countries. Interestingly, several countries achieved significant shipment volumes without an FTA, indicating that they operate relatively free from potential disadvantages.

Next, the Delays section reveals concerning trends, with more than half of recorded shipments experiencing delays. The top performers in terms of shipment delays predominantly consist of German companies, indicating the need for Germany to review its shipment policies and processes. Other countries, including France, Japan, and the US FTA partners, also face challenges in ensuring timely deliveries and should evaluate their shipment efficiency.

Furthermore, as discussed in the Trends section, the COVID-19 pandemic had a profound impact on global shipping and trade, resulting in disruptions and fluctuations in shipment counts. The initial months of the pandemic saw a significant decline in shipments as lockdowns and restrictions affected manufacturing, consumer demand, and logistics - ocean freights and shipment deliveries included. However, as economies gradually reopened and adapted to the new normal, there was a recovery in shipment volumes. Certain countries, such as Panama, Singapore, the UK, and Hong Kong, demonstrated resilience and played crucial roles in facilitating global trade during this challenging period.

Lastly, the Disruptions section highlights the geopolitical risks and local crises such as the Russo-Ukrainian war and the Beirut Port Explosion that can significantly affect the shipping industry. It is crucial for stakeholders to stay vigilant and adapt their strategies to mitigate the impact of such disruptions.

Technical

Leveraging cloud computing, particularly on AWS, offers significant advantages for big data analytics. It enables efficient processing of large volumes of data, facilitates integration with advanced analytics tools, and provides valuable insights for data-driven decision-making. However, careful resource management, consideration of dataset size and characteristics, and attention to security and compliance are essential.

The conversion of files from CSV to Parquet format proved highly beneficial in terms of space savings and faster processing. However, it may not be suitable for small datasets or scenarios involving high write frequency. Parquet's compatibility and suitability should be evaluated based on specific use cases and data requirements.

Moreover, AWS EMR provides flexibility and speed for big data processing, simplifying analysis compared to traditional servers. Scalability and integration with other AWS services enhance data ingestion and analysis. However, expertise in managing EMR clusters and optimizing resource configurations (NetApp, n.d.) is necessary to ensure cost-effectiveness and efficient performance.

Lastly, AWS Data Exchange offers a wide range of free datasets, simplifying data transfer between repositories. Users should exercise caution when subscribing to datasets, as some may come with associated costs. Understanding pricing information and evaluating the value and relevance of each dataset helps manage expenses effectively.

Recommendations

Case Study

  • To further enhance trade volumes, countries with low shipment numbers, such as Peru, should reassess their trade and taxation policies. It is also important for countries to consider the advantages and disadvantages of FTAs and explore alternative trade strategies to foster growth and strengthen trade relationships with the United States. Moreover, the ongoing trade agreement negotiation between the United Kingdom and the US reflects the UK's significant investment and export market potential. This negotiation could inspire other countries to pursue similar agreements based on their shipment volumes and potential benefits.

  • To improve shipment efficiency and address delays in the supply chain, it is important to consider unforeseen disruptions that can impact the movement of goods. These disruptions include natural disasters, political unrest, and pandemics. To mitigate the effects of such events, it is recommended to develop robust contingency plans, diversify transportation routes, and maintain effective communication channels. By preparing for unforeseen disruptions, countries and companies can minimize delays and ensure a more reliable supply chain.

  • To address the challenges brought by the COVID-19 pandemic and improve the resilience and efficiency of the global shipping industry, it is recommended to enhance supply chain resilience, embrace digitalization and automation, strengthen collaboration and communication among stakeholders, and invest in infrastructure and logistics capabilities. These measures will enable countries and companies to better adapt to disruptions.

  • To foster a resilient shipping industry amidst recent disruptions, businesses should assess geopolitical risks, diversify trade partners, enhance supply chain visibility, strengthen crisis management capabilities, and collaborate with industry associations. These measures will help navigate challenges, ensure stability, and build a more adaptive and resilient shipping sector.

Technical

To optimize cost efficiency and enhance analysis capabilities, it is recommended to adjust cluster sizes based on the dataset's actual size. This ensures resources are right-sized, minimizing wastage and resulting in cost savings. Additionally, leveraging machine learning techniques, such as time series analysis, can enable accurate shipment forecasting, allowing for better planning and decision-making in logistics operations.

In constructing an ETL pipeline in AWS for data processing and automation, consider utilizing AWS Glue (aws, n.d.) (Bok, 2020), a fully managed ETL service. AWS Glue simplifies the process by offering a serverless environment for data extraction, transformation, and loading. This eliminates the need for extensive Python scripting, reduces operational overhead, and enables efficient data processing and automation at scale.

To enhance the analysis of the dataset for shippers and ports, incorporate Natural Language Processing (NLP) and geospatial analysis techniques (Hu & Adams, n.d.) (Sohail, 2020). By leveraging NLP, addresses can be interpreted, and relevant information such as city, state, and country can be accurately extracted and tagged. This enriched data provides deeper insights, enabling more granular analysis and a better understanding of the geographical distribution of shipments, facilitating improved decision-making for shippers and ports.

By implementing these strategies, businesses can achieve cost savings, accurate forecasting, streamlined data processing, and enhanced analysis capabilities in the context of shipments and logistics (Tsolaki, et. al., 2022).

Further Studies

  • Expand the dataset's timeline coverage to provide a broader historical context. While the 2018-2020 data offered valuable insights, including a longer timeframe would facilitate the analysis of disruptions and current events that are time-dependent or sensitive. This would enable a more comprehensive understanding of trade dynamics and their evolution over time.

  • Investigate the categories of imported/exported goods and analyze the variations in tariffs imposed on different types of goods. Mapping these goods as specialized products for shippers and countries would reveal how they impact overall trade, agreement negotiations, and supply chain operations. This analysis would provide valuable insights into the composition and dynamics of trade flows.

  • Consider expanding the scope of analysis beyond ocean freights to include other freight modes such as land and air shipments, or combinations of modes. This broader perspective would offer a more comprehensive understanding of the transportation landscape and reveal unique insights into the interplay between different modes of transportation in global trade.

  • Examine the correlation between shipment figures in the dataset and GDP to assess the impact of trade on economic growth. Understanding how trade volumes affect GDP can inform policy decisions and provide insights into the economic benefits derived from international trade. This analysis would help policymakers gauge the effectiveness of trade policies and their implications for economic development.
